definition.value: Electrolysis performed on the face (and oftentimes the neck).

Electrolysis performed on the genitalia and surrounding genital region. Performed oftentimes on cisgender and transgender women for various reasons, including cultural aesthetics and sometimes as a requirement before undergoing genital gender confirmation surgery.
A pre-production process for selecting a certain type of actor, dancer, singer, or extra for a particular role or part in a script, screenplay, or teleplay.

Casting which considers casting or specifically casts persons for roles which they may have not been considered for in the past for any of various reasons, including structural discrimination processes.
The practice of casting without considering the actor's ethnicity and/or skin color.
A representative of the Actors' Equity Association has disputed the use of the term "color blind", preferring the definition "nontraditional casting".
A form of nontraditional casting in acting which revolves around reversing the gender of characters being played (male characters being played by female actors and vice versa).

A form of nontraditional casting in acting which revolves around reversing the race of characters being played (white characters being played by Black actors and vice versa). The concept was intended as a way to open up non-traditional character roles to more actors but has received complaints that it waters down racial differences.
Hostility to, prejudice, or discrimination against Romani peoples (Roma, Sinti, Iberian Kale, Welsh Kale, Finnish Kale and Romanichal).
Fairness of treatment concerning people of different races resulting in equitable opportunities and outcomes for all.

The study of social, political, and economic relations between racial groups at all levels of society. This area encompasses the study of systemic racism, like residential segregation and other complex social processes between different racial groups.

The study of the structures that produce white privilege, the examination of what whiteness is when analyzed as a race, a culture, and a source of systemic racism, and the exploration of other social phenomena generated by the societal compositions, perceptions and group behaviours of white people.
A sense of group or collective identity based on one's perception that they shares a common heritage with a particular racial group.
A sense of group or collective identity based on one's perception of their own Blackness and the specific cultural, social, and political contexts in which Blackness exists.
A sense of group or collective identity based on one's perception of their own whiteness and the specific cultural, social, and political contexts in which "whiteness" exists.

A person who is white, usually used to refer exclusively to persons of European descent (or simply to refer to persons who are not of color, depending on a specific socio-political and historical context).
White persons categorized by nationality.
A member of a racial group of Americans who identify as and are perceived to be white people.

Any of various defensive responses by white people to discussions of societal discrimination, structural racism, and white privilege. It can also find expression in response to the historical analysis of the Atlantic slave trade and European colonization, or the present-day legacy of these systems in modern society.

A form of white defensiveness which can find expression in the claim that racism simply doesn't exist or in the suggestion that slavery in the United States was a benign system or even had a civilizing effect on African Americans.

A phenomenon where white people may obstruct dialogue regarding race-based discrimination, or otherwise block acknowledgement of these factors in society. This proposed form of white defensiveness can seek to reorientate blame towards people of color and Indigenous peoples.
Defensiveness or general discomfort experienced by a white person or white people when confronted with information concerning racial inequality and injustice.

A term used to refer to white Americans who are not "Old Stock" (Anglo-Americans) or White Anglo-Saxon Protestants (WASPs). The term usually refers to the descendants of immigrants from Southern, Central and Eastern Europe, Ireland, the Caucasus, and France/Francophone Canada.
A white American descended from the original settlers of the Thirteen Colonies, of mostly white British ancestry, who colonized America in the 17th and the 18th centuries.
Direct or indirect expressions of speech from persons of color, including writing, speaking, directing, and producing.
A social phenomenon grown out of the heightened interconnectivity between people and the receding economic and social significance of boundaries among nation states.
An alteration or difference from a norm or standard, or a purported norm or standard.
Althought they are conceptually synonymous, deviation usually carries a negative connotation.
The allowable deviation from a standard; a permissible difference.
http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C43414
The allowing, permitting, or acceptance of an action, idea, object, or person which one dislikes or disagrees with.
Tolerance of religions or religious groups within a socio-political context.
A condtion which occurs when a person believes they have done something wrong by surviving a traumatic event when others did not, often feeling self-guilt.
A term used to describe the reactions and behaviors of people who have survived massive and adverse events, such as the Holocaust, the Rape of Nanking, and the HIV/AIDS epidemic.

When the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders IV (DSM-IV) was published, survivor guilt was removed as a recognized specific diagnosis, and redefined as a significant symptom of post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).

A syndrome defined by the psychological effects of living with the long-term trajectory of the AIDS epidemic and includes survivor's guilt, depression, and feelings of being forgotten in contemporary discussions concerning HIV.
Non-random movement of an object(s) from one location to another.
Movement of residence from one place to another. Includes nomadism; labor or seasonal migration; patterns of rural, urban, or suburban migration; or voluntary or forced relocation.
The process whereby a society changes from a rural to an urban way of life. It refers also to the gradual increase in the proportion of people living in urban areas.
The philosophical theory that all events are determined completely by previously existing causes.

The belief that human behavior is directly controlled by an individual's genes or some component of their physiology, generally at the expense of the role of the environment, whether in embryonic development or in learning.
The theory that social interactions and constructs alone determine individual behavior (as opposed to biological or objective factors).
The theory that widely shared practice determines social outcomes, even unconsciously.
The experience of one's own personality or individuality.
An awareness of how one's values, aspirations, and identity fit with their environment and impact others.
An awareness of how one's values, aspirations, and identity cause one to be viewed by others.
Self-awareness of one's racial identity and its relationship to themself and their environment.
The self-awareness of one's status as white or belonging to a race considered white within a specific socio-political and historical context.
Subgroup within a community which has been racialized; alternatively a subgroup within a community which belongs to a socially constructed racial category.

An approach to justice in which one of the responses to a crime is to organize a meeting between the victim and the offender, sometimes with representatives of the wider community. The goal is for them to share their experience of what happened, to discuss who was harmed by the crime and how, and to create a consensus for what the offender can do to repair the harm from the offense. This may include a payment of money given from the offender to the victim, apologies and other amends, and other actions to compensate those affected and to prevent the offender from causing future harm.

A concept in the environmental justice movement, which developed in the United States throughout the 1970s and 1980s. The term is used to describe environmental injustice that occurs within a racialized context both in practice and policy. In the United States, environmental racism criticizes inequalities between urban and exurban areas after white flight. Internationally, environmental racism can refer to the effects of the global waste trade, like the negative health impact of the export of electronic waste to China from developed countries.
Racism which is endemic and especially widespread within a particular society, group, and/or area.

A Mexican person of predominantly Sub-Saharan African descent and heritage. As a single population, Afro-Mexicans includes individuals descended from Black slaves brought to Mexico during the colonial era in the transatlantic African slave trade, as well as others of more recent immigrant African descent, including Afro-descended persons from neighboring English, French, and Spanish-speaking countries of the Caribbean and Central America, descendants of fugitive slaves who escaped to Mexico from the Southern United States, and to a lesser extent recent immigrants directly from Africa.
Note that the term "Blaxican" should only be used by members identifying within that community.
More broadly, this term (and its synonyms) may include persons identifying as both African American and Mexican American.
A type of justice accessible primarily or assisted primarily through digital means; alternatively, social justice within digital environments.
